@flexiarg peeragogy/curating-not-experting
@title Hold a Curatorial Stance, Not an Expert One, Toward the Conversation You Convene
@keywords curator, expertise, stance, connective-intelligence, anti-credentialism, facilitation, kiko-lab
@audience peer-learning facilitators, project conveners, conversation hosts
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/roles peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/polling-for-ideas peeragogy/discerning-a-pattern]

! conclusion: A peer-learning practice runs into trouble when its facilitators position themselves as either experts (talking down to the group) or as flat-equals (refusing to bring stewardship).  The curating-not-experting stance is a third position: bring people into conversation, hold the shape of the inquiry, and invite expertise from wherever it actually lives — which is often distributed across the group, not concentrated in one person.  The stance distinguishes peeragogy from both top-down pedagogy and from leaderless co-learning.
  + context: A facilitator convenes a group around a topic the facilitator is interested in.  A pure expert stance positions the facilitator as the source of knowledge; the group's job becomes receiving.  A pure peer stance refuses to acknowledge that the facilitator is doing real work in shaping the inquiry; the group's job becomes nothing in particular and the inquiry drifts.  The curating-not-experting stance is what works in practice: the facilitator is not the source of the knowledge but is responsible for the shape of the conversation, the choice of who's at the table, and the integration of what surfaces.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: stewardship ↔ expert-authority.
    Real: groups need someone to hold the shape of an inquiry — without that, conversations meander and don't accumulate.  But if the shape-holder claims to be the expert on the content, the group's other voices recede and the inquiry contracts to one perspective.
    Irreducible: facilitation is real labor; flat-equality denies it.  Expertise is also real; pretending no one has more knowledge than anyone else is a fiction.  The curating stance acknowledges both without conflating them.
    Active: the pull recurs every time the facilitator is asked a substantive question they could either answer or redirect, and every time the conversation drifts and someone needs to bring it back without imposing.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Source naming: when a substantive question arises that the facilitator could answer, the facilitator instead names whose expertise — in the room or beyond — would be most apt, and brings them in.
    (2) Shape-holding: the facilitator articulates the inquiry's question(s) explicitly, returns to them when the conversation drifts, and tracks which questions are still open.
    (3) Voice-curation: the facilitator notices which voices haven't spoken and creates space for them, without putting individuals on the spot.
    (4) Integrative wrap: at session close, the facilitator names what the conversation surfaced — not a verdict on what's true, but a curatorial summary of what was said and where it points.
    (5) Connective intelligence: the facilitator treats the conversation as a node in a wider network — explicitly bringing in other practitioners, projects, or threads the group should know about.  (Doug Engelbart lineage; named operationally in Kiko Lab's framing.)
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: participants can identify the facilitator's role as something other than "the expert in the room" AND as something other than "a peer like everyone else."  The facilitator is doing legible work but isn't claiming to be the source.  Failing when: either participants defer to the facilitator as the authority, or the facilitator disclaims any role and the inquiry loses its shape.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Question-funneling: substantive questions all route through the facilitator, who answers them as the expert.
    - Shape-collapse: without the facilitator actively holding the inquiry, the conversation drifts and doesn't accumulate.
    - Performance-of-flatness: the facilitator refuses to acknowledge their convening labor, which leaves the group unable to credit, extend, or eventually take it over.
    - Voice-monoculture: the same few voices dominate because no one is curating who speaks.
    - Expert-arrival defaulting: when an expert joins the conversation, the room reorganises around them as authority instead of as one voice the curator brought in.
